rentage: Family Law’s Equality Project in Our Empirical Age -- t12. Can Parenting Be Equal? Rethinking Equality and Gender Differences in Parenting -- tPart VII: Globalization and Parenthood: How Do Family Immigration and Transnational Parenting Shape Parenthood? How Should They Inform Debates over Parenthood? -- t13. Transnationalism of the Heart: Familyhood across Borders -- t14. Transnational Mothering and Models of Parenthood: Ideological and Intergenerational Challenges in Filipina Migrant Families -- tPart VIII: Now What? Given Current Indicators, Can the “Toothpaste Go Back in the Tube”? Should It? -- t15. Of Human Bonding: Integrating the Needs and Desires of Women, Men, and the Children Their Unions Produce -- t16. The Other Side of the Demographic Revolution: Social Policy and Responsible Parenthood -- tEpilogue -- tAbout the Contributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aExtraordinary changes in patterns of family life-and family law-have dramatically altered the boundaries of parenthood and opened up numerous questions and debates. What is parenthood and why does it matter? How should society define, regulate, and support it? Is parenthood separable from marriage-or couplehood-when society seeks to foster children’s well-being? What is the better model of parenthood from the perspective of child outcomes? Intense disagreements over the definition and future of marriage often rest upon conflicting convictions about parenthood. What Is Parenthood? asks bold and direct questions about parenthood in contemporary society, and it brings together a stellar interdisciplinary group of scholars with widely varying perspectives to investigate them. Editors Linda C. McClain and Daniel Cere facilitate a dynamic conversation between scholars from several disciplines about competing models of parenthood and a sweeping array of topics, including single parenthood, adoption, donor-created families, gay and lesbian parents, transnational parenthood, parent-child attachment, and gender difference and parenthood.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aAdoptionxLaw and legislationxUnited States. 0aAdoptionxLaw and legislationzUnited States. 0aCustody of childrenxUnited States. 0aCustody of childrenzUnited States. 0aGay parentsxLegal status, laws, etcxUnited States. 0aGay parentsxLegal status, laws, etczUnited States. 0aGay parentsxLegal status, laws, etc.zUnited States. 0aParent and child (Law)xUnited States. 0aParent and child (Law)zUnited States. 0aParenthoodxUnited States. 0aParenthoodzUnited States. 7aLAW / General.2bisacsh1 aBrinig, Margaret F., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrowning, Don, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCahn, Naomi, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCarbone, June, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCere, Daniel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCere, Daniel, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aDoucet, Andrea, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFrelich Appleton, Susan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHébert, Terence E., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMarquardt, Elizabeth, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMcClain, Linda C., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMcClain, Linda C., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aMeyer, David D., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMoss, Ellen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/v